/wiki/Church_of_St._Olaf,_Jomala: The Church of St. Olaf is a medieval stone church in Jomala, Åland Islands. It belongs to the Evangelical Lutheran Church of Finland. Dating from about 1260 to 1280, it is possibly the oldest Christian church in Finland, and was extended in the 19th century. It is constructed of local red granite and limestone. The church is dedicated to King Olaf II of Norway, patron saint of the Åland Islands and Jomala.
/wiki/Jomala: Jomala is a municipality of Åland, an autonomous territory of Finland.

Eckerö is a municipality of Åland, an autonomous territory under Finnish sovereignty. The municipality has a population of 957
(31 January 2019) and covers an area of 752.67 square kilometres (290.61 sq mi) of
which 644.94 km2 (249.01 sq mi)
is water. The population density is
8.89 inhabitants per square kilometre (23.0/sq mi).

/wiki/List_of_medieval_stone_churches_in: This is a list of medieval stone churches in Finland. A total number of 104 fieldstone churches were built between the 13th and 16th century, of which 83 have been preserved. Numbers include the sacristies of uncompleted churches as well as three churches in Vyborg which is now part of Russia.
